System

Task 4 Aurora
Aurora is a Windows endpoint agent that uses Sigma rules and indicators of compromise to detect threats. It collects data using ETW and matches it against detection rules.

Aurora only logs events when a rule is triggered. This reduces noise and makes analysis easier compared to tools like Sysmon.

Aurora can be customized with different rule sets and can run locally without sending data outside the network. There are two versions, Aurora and Aurora Lite. The main difference is that the full version includes additional rule sets and features.

Aurora uses presets to control detection behavior. These presets are Standard, Reduced, Minimal, and Intense. The Intense preset detects more events and uses the highest CPU.

Aurora can be run from the command line or as a service. It also provides useful options such as checking status, tracing events, and exporting logs.

Aurora supports multiple output methods including Event Viewer, log files, and network output.

Aurora can also perform response actions when a rule is triggered. These include killing a process, suspending it, or creating a memory dump. Custom actions can also be defined.

Aurora uses event IDs to categorize alerts. For example, Event ID 1 represents process creation and Event ID 103 indicates that the Aurora agent has stopped.

